 from mitmproxy\\n  - Error: `HttpSyntaxException(\\\"Invalid chunked encoding length: b'Q'\\\")`\\n  - Finding: mitmproxy 6.0.2 validates HTTP syntax strictly, rejecting malformed requests\\n  \\n- **TE.CL Attack** (Transfer-Encoding before Content-Length):\\n  - Result: **HTTP 200 OK** (request accepted with valid chunked encoding)\\n  - Finding: mitmproxy prioritizes Transfer-Encoding over Content-Length (RFC compliant)\\n\\n**3. Internal Endpoint Enumeration:**\\nAll tested endpoints returned **404 Not Found**:\\n- `/api/admin`, `/api/config`, `/proxy`, `/internal`, `/backend`, `/status`, `/health`, `/api/status`, `/config`, `/admin`, `/debug`, `/metrics`\\n\\n**Exception:**\\n- `/server-status` \u2192 **HTTP 403 Forbidden** (endpoint exists, reveals backend: \\\"Apache/2.4.65 (Debian) Server at haproxy Port 8001\\\")\\n\\n### Proxy Architecture Discovered\\n\\n```\\nCLIENT \u2192 mitmproxy (port 32900) \u2192 HAProxy (port 8001, internal) \u2192 Apache/2.4.65 (Flask app)\\n```\\n\\n### Key Findings\\n\\n**CRITICAL:** `/admin_panel` endpoint shows **NO REAL ACCESS CONTROL** based on headers:\\n- Returns HTTP 200 with both `X-Forwarded-For: 127.0.0.1` and `Host: localhost`\\n- However, displays JavaScript modal: \\\"Only administrator users can open this section\\\"\\n- **This is client-side validation only** - not true IP-based access control\\n\\n**Request Smuggling Risk:** MEDIUM-LOW\\n- mitmproxy validates chunked encoding strictly at Layer 1\\n- Malformed requests are rejected before reaching backend\\n- TE.CL desync unlikely due to strict HTTP parsing\\n\\n**Information Disclosure:** CONFIRMED\\n- `/server-status` error messages leak internal architecture:\\n  - Backend hostname: \\\"haproxy\\\"\\n  - Backend port: 8001\\n  - Apache version: 2.4.65 (Debian)\\n\\n**Proxy Header Injection:** POSSIBLE\\n- No proxy headers added automatically (no Via, X-Forwarded-For in responses)\\n- X-Forwarded-For/X-Real-IP headers NOT validated or stripped\\n- Could potentially be used for IP spoofing if backend trusts these headers\\n\\n### Security Implications\\n\\n1. **No True Header-Based Access Control**: The `/admin_panel` endpoint accepts requests regardless of X-Forwarded-For or Host header values, indicating the application doesn't implement IP-based access restrictions at the backend level. The \\\"administrator only\\\" restriction is enforced client-side via JavaScript modal.\\n\\n2. **No Internal-Only Endpoints Found**: None of the common internal API endpoints (`/api/admin`, `/api/config`, `/internal`, etc.) exist or are accessible via header manipulation.\\n\\n3. **Request Smuggling Protected**: The mitmproxy layer provides strong protection against HTTP request smuggling attacks by strictly validating request syntax.\\n\\n## Proofs\\n\\n**Test 1: X-Forwarded-For header on /admin_panel**\\n```\\n> GET /admin_panel HTTP/1.1\\n> Host: 127.0.0.1:32900\\n> Cookie: session=58P3X-jvhvlu5K4TJVpzuTVwTbpzpmq1-GjZz0CtaeM\\n> X-Forwarded-For: 127.0.0.1\\n\\n< HTTP/1.1 200 OK\\n< Server: Apache/2.4.65 (Debian)\\n< Content-Length: 5293\\n\\n<div class=\\\"modal-body\\\">\\n    Only administrator users can open this section.\\n</div>\\n```\\n\\n**Test 2: Request Smuggling - CL.TE Attack**\\n```\\nPOST /dashboard HTTP/1.1\\nHost: 127.0.0.1:32900\\nContent-Length: 4\\nTransfer-Encoding: chunked\\n\\nHTTP/1.1 400 Bad Request\\nServer: mitmproxy 6.0.2\\nConnection: close\\n\\nHttpSyntaxException(\\\"Invalid chunked encoding length: b'Q'\\\")\\n```\\n\\n**Test 3: Information Disclosure - /server-status**\\n```\\nGET /server-status HTTP/1.1\\nHTTP/1.1 403 Forbidden\\n\\n<address>Apache/2.4.65 (Debian) Server at haproxy Port 8001</address>\\n```\\n\\n## Confidence Score\\n\\n**0.7** - Strong evidence of proxy architecture and header handling behavior, but no actual localhost-only endpoints discovered that bypass normal access controls.\\n\\n## Thoughts\\n\\nThe testing revealed that:\\n1. The proxy chain (mitmproxy \u2192 HAProxy \u2192 Apache) is well-configured against request smuggling\\n2. No true internal-only endpoints were found that become accessible via header manipulation\\n3. The `/admin_panel` endpoint doesn't implement IP-based access control at the backend - it relies on session-based authentication and client-side JavaScript for admin restriction\\n4. The application doesn't appear to have separate internal/external API surfaces that respond differently based on X-Forwarded-For or similar headers\\n5. The main vulnerability is information disclosure via `/server-status` error messages revealing backend architecture\\n\\nNext steps would be to focus on application-level vulnerabilities rather than proxy/header manipulation attacks, as the infrastructure appears well-protected against HTTP smuggling and doesn't expose internal-only endpoints.\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":106730,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":1593,\"service_tier\":\"standard\"}}\n",
